subSubSection.paragraph:
Head
(
Figs 1–3
). Ocellar triangle narrow, extending to the ptilineal suture. Six pairs of frontal setae; one pair of upper orbital setae; ocellar setae well developed; postocellar setae same length as ocellar pair; inner convergent and outer divergent vertical setae shorter than ocellar setae. Antenna (
Figs 2–3
). Postpedicel 2× length of pedicel. Arista long, wider on basal fourth, shortly pubescent.

Abdomen
(
Figs 1, 6
). Longer than thorax. Tergites I–VI with lateral setae slightly more developed than the others. Sternite 5 with lower margin concave, upper margin rounded, covered with setae, scarcer in the basal half and two long, stout and brown setae in the lobes (
Fig. 7
).

Terminalia
(
Figs 8–13
). 
Epand
large, rounded and divided in the center (
Fig. 8
); 
cerc
setulose, longer than wide, with lateral margins slightly straight, basal half rounded, apical half V-shaped (
Figs 10–11
). 
Sur
long, about the same length of cercus (
Figs 8–10
). Phallic complex: 
hypd
short, as long as it is wide, upper anterior margin sinuous; 
pregt
longer, longer than wide, somewhat triangle-shaped; 
pgt
short, rounded, with membranous apex; 
epiph
long, straight, with membranous apex; 
distph
curved with membranous apex; 
phapod
long and curved on apex (
Figs 12–13
).

